    "#### Example 2\n",
    "\n",
    "Now let's say we have three classes of size 5, 10, and 150, and choose one at random.  The expectation of our class size is.  "
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "### Variance "
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "![](./resources/mean-vs-variance.png)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "So one way of describing this is the amount of spread involved.  So how far are the values from one another.\n",
    "\n",
    "$Var(X) = E[(X - u)^2] =  \\sum_x(x - u)^2p(x) $\n",
    "\n",
    "Intuitively this is the weighted average distance of a sample to the mean.\n",
    "\n",
    "How far away are our set of samples away from the mean.\n",
    "\n",
    "* Take a random variable, and subtract the mean of the random variable and square the difference.  This is the variance.\n",
    "\n",
    "• SD(X) = Var(x)\n",
    "\t• Variance is in units squared\n",
    "\t• Standard deviation is the same deviation "
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Different way of writing variance:\n",
    "\n",
    "*$Var(X) = E[X^2] - E[X]^2$\n",
    "\n",
    "> So these two terms are very different.  The first one is if you take X and square it, what is the expectation of the result of that.  And the other is what's the expectation of X, and then square it.\n",
    "\n",
    "For example if we let X be the value of rolling a 6 sided die, then:\n",
    "\n",
    "* $E[X^2] = 1^2(1/6) + 2^2(1/6) + 3^2(1/6) ...  = 91/6$\n",
    "* $(E[X])^2 = (7/2)^2$\n",
    "* So variance is $E[X^2] - (E[X])^2 = 35/12$\n",
    "This is the numerical description of spread."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "#### Probability Mass Function\n",
    "\n",
    "1. As a function/dictionary \n",
    "\n",
    "For a discrete random variable, we have a mapping between the values a random variable can take on, and the probability of that value.\n",
    "\n",
    "And the PMF for a discrete RV is just a histogram.  \n",
    "\n",
    "![](./resources/pmf-two-dice-rolls.png)\n",
    "\n",
    "![](./resources/one-die-roll.png)\n",
    "\n",
    "Note that $P_x(x)$ completely describes a discrete random variable.  Or in other words, knowing this function, we can determine anything else one might want to know about a random variable.  It must be the case that P(x)x = 1.\n",
    "\n",
    "#### Our first probability distribution: Coin flips \n",
    "\n",
    "Let X = number of heads after a coin is flipped three times. What is the probability of\n",
    "the set of different outcomes?\n",
    "\n",
    "* So far we have calculate the probability of a given event occurring \n",
    "* But we know that really, we can expect a range of outcomes \n",
    "* And this is by definition, after for an outcome to be in our sample space, the outcome not zero"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "${n \\choose k} p^k(1-p)^{n-k}$\n",
    "> This is because there are ${n \\choose k}$ orderings and $p^k(1-p)^{n-k}$ is the probability of one particular ordering.\n",
    "\n",
    "#### Binomial Random Variable\n",
    "\n",
    "1. The number of observations n is fixed.\n",
    "2. Each observation is independent.\n",
    "3. Each observation represents one of two outcomes (\"success\" or \"failure\").\n",
    "4. The probability of \"success\" p is the same for each outcome."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "### Example - brown eyed children\n",
    "\n",
    "> We are trying to predict the number of browned eyed children from a couple.  Both mom and dad are Bb, Bb.  \n",
    "\n",
    "* Child has brown eyes if either or both are B.  \n",
    "* Only if bb does he get blue eyes.  \n",
    "* There are four children.  What is the probability three have brown eyes.\n",
    "\n",
    "Probability \n",
    "\n",
    "|               |  MB           | Mb    |\n",
    "| ------------- |:-------------:| -----:|\n",
    "|       DB      | BB            | Bb    |\n",
    "|       Db      | bB            |   bb  |"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "> So we could calculate this, but once you think of this in terms of these distributions you get better at translating these problems into these distributions."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "### Properties of a binomial"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "* E[X] = np \n",
    "> n experiments, p of them to be success, the expected number of successes is n*p\n",
    "> Makes sense because \n",
    "\n",
    "* Var(x) = np(1 - p)\n",
    "\n",
    "Example of expectation \n",
    "* Flip a coin three times, what is the expected number of heads."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "\n",
    "* 0:$ {3\\choose0} (.5)^3 => .125*1 = .125$\n",
    "\n",
    "* 1: $ {3\\choose1}(.5)^3 => .125*3 = .375$\n",
    "\n",
    "* 2: $ {3\\choose 2} (.5)^3 => .125*3 = .375$\n",
    "\n",
    "* 3: $ {3\\choose 3} (.5)^3 => .125*1 = .125$\n",
    "\n",
    "Next step take the weighted sum "
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "### On to the next one\n",
    "\n",
    "\n",
    "\n",
    "* We let students retake an exam for mod 4 as many times as they want\n",
    "* The probability of passing is .2 \n",
    "What is the probability that it takes 3 tries before passing?\n",
    "\n",
    "> X is number of independent trials until the first success\n",
    "> p is the probability of success of each trial \n",
    "\n",
    "### properties\n",
    "\n",
    "$P(X = x) = (1 - p)^{n - 1} \\times p$ \n",
    "\n",
    "\n",
    "$E(x) = 1/p $\n",
    "$ Var(X) = \\frac{1 - p}{p^2} $ \n",
    "\n",
    "* Flipping a coin until the first head appears\n",
    "* Or draw cards (with replacement), and probability until the first ace appears."
   ]
